      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Introduction</h3>Since the names of Maya leaders are generally not known to most people, we will use the terms \"king\" and \"kings\" in this text. However, we will always append the Maya terms <i>ajaw</i> (singular) and <i>ajawob</i> (plural) alongside them (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fee902e4-93b5-472e-bea8-b657b5a8737d",
                     "text": "McKinney, K. J.",
                     "page": "pp. 14",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2011",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2011",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_family",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>The Altar Q</h3>In this text, we will continue exploring the significance of Altar Q in Copán, Honduras:</p><p><div class=\"htSlides\"></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Slide 1</b>: Images of Altar Q at the archaeological site of Copán, Honduras. Photo taken during a visit on <htdate0>.<br />The names of the kings, or <i>ajawob</i>, are documented by Anastasia Hutnick, Catherine Docter and Dorie R. Budet (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>).<br />he source code for these slides was inspired by code from W3Schools (<htcite2>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "85c2d88c-6ad8-4858-95f8-0f157c49bf07",
                     "text": "Hutnick, Anastasia",
                     "page": "pp. 18, 35 - 67.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ccf473d0-069a-4c7e-a0ac-690a47670648",
                     "text": "Docter, Catherine. Budet, Dorie R.",
                     "page": "pp. 60",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2005",
                        "month": "08",
                        "day": "04"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cf7adc72-d340-412e-8d48-953ac64cb670",
                     "text": "W3Schools",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "-1",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2020",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2005",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The altar is shaped like a big box, with inscriptions on top and sculpted human figures on its sides.",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>Altar Q depicts 16 kings ( <i>ajawob</i>), which we will treat didactically as consecutive generations, despite lacking evidence that they were actually consecutive generations (<htcite0>). Through this representation, <i>Yax Pasaj Chan Yopaat</i>, is shown alongside his 15 predecessors, emphasizing the continuity of his royal lineage.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "85c2d88c-6ad8-4858-95f8-0f157c49bf07",
                     "text": "Hutnick, Anastasia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2020",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_numbers",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Families and the numbers: The Hundreds</h3>Continuing with our analogy between families and numbers (<htcite0>), let’s explore the first three generations of the Copán kings (<i>ajawob</i>) alongside their corresponding decimal numbers:</p><p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th><i>Son</i></th><th>Father</th><th>Grandfather</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\">&nbsp;</td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"><i>K’inich Popol Hol</i></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"><i>K’inich Yax K’uk’ Mo’</i></td></tr> <tr id=\"tf2\"><td id=\"tc1f2\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\">2</span></td> <td id=\"tc2f2\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\">1</span></td> <td id=\"tc3f2\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\">0</span></td></tr> </table><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Number positions represented as a family.</p><p>When a grandson is born, a new generation is added to the family. Similarly, numbers increase when they reach their maximum value, which in the decimal system is 9. Let’s examine this concept in action. Using the arrows, observe the numbers following 89 and 99:</p><p><table id=\"yupana1\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Hindo-Arabic name</i></th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\" colspan=\"4\"></td> <td> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></i></td></tr></table><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 2</b>: Counting numbers between 89 and 100.</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Rules for Growth</b><br />Just as our height increases due to factors like nutrition, numbers also follow specific rules to grow. Some of these rules have already been introduced, but before proceeding, can you define some rules for increasing numbers?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "00f3ab60-2017-420a-99dc-56de384243e8",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Numerical Families",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "09",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_numeric_table",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Expanding generations and numbers</h3>Based on our previous discussion, we can conclude that numbers increase according to the following rules:</p><p><ol><li>Each digit in a number can have a value ranging from the minimum (0) to the maximum (9).</li><li>When a digit reaches its maximum value (9), it resets to the minimum value (0), and the digit to its immediate left increases by one. If no digit is visible in the next position, it is assumed to be a \"hidden\" zero (0), representing an empty place (<htcite0>).</li><li>To change the leftmost digit again, the preceding digit must count from zero (0) to nine (9).</li></ol></p><p>Just as people have names, so do the generations and positions in numerical order. The table below shows the relationship between the kings depicted on Altar Q, their generational names, the corresponding numerical order, the range of numbers used in that order, and the minimum and maximum values in each position:</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "576e4648-77fa-4a6d-9e51-9459ced964f3",
                     "text": "Musa, Auwalu",
                     "page": "pp. 44, 46 - 48",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "19"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2014",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"yupana2\" class=\"tawapukllay\"> <tr><th>King (<i>Ajaw</i>)</th><th>Generation</th><th>Order</th><th>Amount of numbers</th><th>First number</th><th>Last number</th></tr> <tr><td><i>Yax Pasaj Chan Yopaat</i></td><td>Son</td><td>Ones</td><td>1</td><td><b>0</b></td><td><b>9</b></td></tr> <tr><td><i>K’ahk’ Yipyaj Chan K’awiil</i></td><td>Father</td><td>Tens</td><td>2</td><td><b>10</b></td><td><b>99</b></td></tr> <tr><td><i>Waxaklajuun Ubaah K’awiil</i></td><td>Grandfather</td><td>Hundreds</td><td>3</td><td><b>100</b></td><td><b>999</b></td></tr> <tr><td><i>K’ahk Uti’ Witz’ K’awiil</i></td><td>1st Great-Grandfather</td><td>Thousands</td><td>4</td><td><b>1,000</b></td><td><b>9,999</b></td></tr> <tr><td><i>Butz’ Chan</i></td><td>2nd Great-Grandfather</td><td>Ten Thousands</td><td>5</td><td><b>10,000</b></td><td><b>99,999</b></td></tr> <tr><td><i>Tzi B’alam</i></td><td>3rd Great-Grandfather</td><td>Hundred Thousands</td><td>6</td><td><b>100,000</b></td><td><b>999,999</b></td></tr> <tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td>4th Great-Grandfather</td><td>Millions</td><td>7</td><td><b>1,000,000</b></td><td><b>9,999,999</b></td></tr> <tr><td><i>Wi’ Yohl K’inich</i></td><td>5th Great-Grandfather</td><td>Ten Millions</td><td>8</td><td><b>10,000,000</b></td><td><b>99,999,999</b></td></tr> <tr><td><i>Bahlam Nehn</i></td><td>6th Great-Grandfather</td><td>Hundred Millions</td><td>9</td><td><b>100,000,000</b></td><td><b>999,999,999</b></td></tr> <tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td>7th Great-Grandfather</td><td>One Billions</td><td>10</td><td><b>1,000,000,000</b></td><td><b>9,999,999,999</b></td></tr> </table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 3</b>: Numerical limits and the family.<br />The names of the kings (<i>ajawob</i>) mentioned in this table are documented by Anastasia Hutnick, Catherine Docter, and Dorie R. Budet (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>).<br />The generational names were sourced from the <i>\"Dicionário de Genealogia\"</i> by Gilber Rubim Rangel (<htcite2> ;<htcite3> ; <htcite4>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
