      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Conclusion</h3>In this text, we have expanded our understanding of numerical systems, particularly emphasizing that when a digit reaches its maximum value, the digit to the left increases by one. In the decimal system, the maximum value for any digit is 9. When all digits in a number reach their limit, the leftmost digit increases by one, while the other digits reset to zero. This observation leads us to an important reflection:</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflexión 2: Is there a limit to numbers?</b><br />Decimal numbers consist of ten digits, ranging from zero (0) to nine (9). These digits set the limit for each position in the system. As we've seen, when a position reaches its maximum value, we can always add another digit by following specific rules. But this raises a critical question: is there a final number?</div></div></center></p><p>We pose this question to our readers but will refrain from answering it immediately. Instead, we will explore these concepts further to reinforce your understanding. In a few pages, we will provide the answer and introduce an important concept that has implications not only in mathematics but also in life.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
